{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T06-43-22-835Z","slug":"developer-workstation-blast-radius","locale":"it","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T06:43:39.234Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2026-05-09--developer-workstation-blast-radius/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2026-05-09--developer-workstation-blast-radius/it/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/developer-workstation-blast-radius/it/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T06-43-22-835Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"2ea2b0fa3efd5f31a991b8add09b755aea04ca443ae149a0b177d9569acefeef","outputHash":"dc2917f868af1af49ca4945367ad18018ffc9f200e29b6b38908fc7e36c6382a","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The articleargues that developers should shrink the “blast radius” of a compromised workstation by adding focused, layered defenses rather than relying on generic corporate policies or extreme “go‑off‑the‑grid” advice. It proposes four practical layers—Isolation (e.g., using narrowly‑configured Dev Containers), Secret handling (replacing plaintext .env files with encrypted or managed secrets like VarLock), Detection (canary tokens and tripwires), and Egress control (monitoring outbound traffic)—and shows how each can be implemented with concrete tooling and configuration examples. The tone is a pragmatic tutorial aimed at software engineers, team leads, and security‑aware developers who need actionable steps to protect their laptops without sacrificing productivity. Recurring metaphors frame the workstation as a “blast‑radius” problem, likening containers to a “suitcase” that carries only what the project needs, and emphasizing “narrow mounts” versus “wet cement” development environments.","totalInputTokens":37367,"totalOutputTokens":6959,"totalCacheReadTokens":19072,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":15017,"totalCostUsd":0.002709933,"pricingSource":"local-openrou